  "prompt": "Are there international laws against money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are several international laws and treaties aimed at combating money laundering. Here are some of the most important ones:\n\n*   **United Nations Convention Against Illicit Traffic in Narcotic Drugs and Psychotropic Substances (1988) (Vienna Convention):** This convention was one of the first international efforts to address money laundering. It required signatory countries to criminalize the laundering of proceeds from drug trafficking and to cooperate in international investigations and prosecutions.\n\n*   **Financial Action Task Force (FATF):** While not a treaty or law itself, the FATF is an inter-governmental body established in 1989. It sets international standards and promotes effective implementation of legal, regulatory, and operational measures for combating money laundering, terrorist financing, and other related threats to the integrity of the international financial system. FATF Recommendations are recognized globally as the international standard for anti-money laundering (AML) and counter-terrorist financing (CFT).\n\n*   **United Nations Convention against Transnational Organized Crime (2000) (Palermo Convention):** This convention broadened the scope of anti-money laundering efforts beyond drug trafficking to include proceeds from a wider range of serious crimes. It also emphasized international cooperation, extradition, and asset recovery.\n\n*   **United Nations Convention against Corruption (2003) (Merida Convention):** This convention focuses on combating corruption, including the laundering of proceeds derived from corrupt acts. It requires signatory countries to criminalize corruption-related offenses and to implement measures to prevent and detect money laundering.\n\n*   **Council of Europe Convention on Laundering, Search, Seizure and Confiscation of the Proceeds from Crime (1990) (Strasbourg Convention):** This convention aimed to facilitate international cooperation in tracing, freezing, seizing, and confiscating the proceeds of crime. It was later updated to address terrorist financing.\n\n*   **European Union Directives:** The European Union has issued several directives on anti-money laundering, which member states are required to implement into their national laws. These directives have evolved over time to address emerging threats and to align with international standards set by the FATF.\n\nThese international laws and agreements provide a framework for countries to cooperate in combating money laundering by:\n\n*   Criminalizing money laundering.\n*   Establishing financial intelligence units (FIUs) to collect and analyze suspicious transaction reports.\n*   Implementing customer due diligence measures by financial institutions.\n*   Facilitating international cooperation in investigations and prosecutions.\n*   Seizing and confiscating the proceeds of crime.\n\nIt's important to note that the effectiveness of these laws depends on the willingness of individual countries to implement and enforce them.\n\n",
